<file path="README.md">
  1: # Next.js 15 Pages Router — Strict Context Render-Order Bug
  2: 
  3: > **Note:** This project was generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code) (AI pair programming). The bug, findings, and fix are real and based on verified Next.js issues — but all code and documentation were written by an AI assistant. Review accordingly before using in production.
  4: 
  5: Minimal reproduction and fix for the error:
  6: 
  7: ```
  8: useFlagsmith must be used within a FlagsmithProvider
  9: ```
 10: 
 11: …thrown in a page component despite `FlagsmithProvider` being correctly placed in `_app.tsx`. The same class of bug affects **any** context built with `createContext(null)` and a consumer that throws (or crashes) when the context is null.
 12: 
 13: ---
 14: 
 15: ## The Bug
 16: 
 17: Next.js 15 Pages Router uses `react-dom-server.edge.production.js` — the Edge streaming renderer — instead of the legacy synchronous `renderToString`. The streaming renderer **does not guarantee parent-before-child render order**. Under certain conditions (Vercel Edge deployment, specific Next.js 15 minor versions) the page component's function body executes **before** `_app` mounts its providers.
 18: 
 19: Evidence captured during debugging:
 20: 
 21: ```js
 22: { ps: 'Page' }   // ← page rendered first
 23: { ps: 'App' }    // ← _app rendered after
 24: ```
 25: 
 26: This is impossible under `renderToString` — it is a property of the streaming renderer.
 27: 
 28: When the page runs before `_app`:
 29: 
 30: 1. `useContext(FlagsmithCtx)` returns `null` (no provider in the tree yet)
 31: 2. `useFlagsmith()` hard-throws: _"must be used within a FlagsmithProvider"_
 32: 3. `useFlags()` crashes with a generic `TypeError: Cannot read properties of null`
 33: 4. `useFlagsmithLoading()` silently returns `undefined` — wrong data, no error
 34: 
 35: Stack traces from the bug point to `react-dom-server.edge.production.js:4282`, confirming the Edge renderer is the culprit even for Pages Router routes without explicit edge runtime configuration.
 36: 
 37: ---
 38: 
 39: ## Repo Structure
 40: 
 41: ```
 42: lib/
 43:   StrictContext.tsx      # Mimics useFlagsmith() — createContext(null) + hard throw
 44:   SafeContext.tsx        # Safe pattern — createContext(defaultValue), never throws
 45:   withStrictContext.tsx  # HOC fix + getServerContextState() server helper
 46: 
 47: pages/
 48:   _app.tsx               # Both providers; Navbar consumes both
 49:   index.tsx              # Broken page — throws at request time (no HOC)
 50:   edge.tsx               # Explicit experimental-edge runtime
 51:   simulate-bug.tsx       # Server-side reproduction via getServerSideProps
 52:   fixed.tsx              # Fixed page — withStrictContext HOC + side-by-side comparison
 53: 
 54: scripts/
 55:   simulate-render-order-bug.mjs  # Standalone proof, no server needed
 56: ```
 57: 
 58: ---
 59: 
 60: ## Quick Start
 61: 
 62: ```bash
 63: npm install
 64: 
 65: # Reproduce the build failure locally (no edge runtime needed)
 66: npm run build:broken
 67: # Expected: next build fails with react-dom-server.edge.production.js:4282
 68: 
 69: # Verify the fixed state builds cleanly
 70: npm run build
 71: 
 72: # See the runtime error reproduced without a server
 73: npm run simulate
 74: 
 75: # Run the dev server and explore the routes below
 76: npm run dev
 77: ```
 78: 
 79: | Route | What it shows |
 80: |---|---|
 81: | `/` | **Broken** — no HOC, no `serverContextState`. Shows `initialized: false` (wrong data). On Vercel Edge: throws. |
 82: | `/simulate-bug` | **Throw reproduced locally** — renders the hook consumer without any provider, catches and displays the exact error |
 83: | `/fixed` | **Fixed** — HOC pattern, both contexts initialized correctly, side-by-side comparison |
 84: | `/edge` | `experimental-edge` runtime — same broken pattern as `/`; throws on Vercel Edge |
 85: 
 86: ---
 87: 
 88: ## Local Reproduction (No Edge Runtime or Vercel Needed)
 89: 
 90: The bug is reproducible with `npm run build:broken` — no Vercel account, no edge runtime config, no deployment.
 91: 
 92: **What `build:broken` does:**
 93: 
 94: 1. Writes a static `pages/index.tsx` with no `getServerSideProps` (opts page into build-time static prerender)
 95: 2. Strips `pages/_app.tsx` of its `StrictContextProvider` (simulates the no-provider scenario)
 96: 3. Runs `next build`
 97: 4. Restores both files — even if the build fails
 98: 
 99: **Expected output:**
100: 
101: ```
102: Error: useStrictContext must be used within a StrictContextProvider
103:     at useStrictContext (lib/StrictContext.tsx:28:11)
104:     at Home (pages/index.tsx:7:15)
105:     at react-dom-server.edge.production.js:4282:23
106: ```
107: 
108: **Why this works:** Next.js 15 uses `react-dom-server.edge.production.js` (the streaming Edge renderer) for static page prerendering at build time — not just for edge runtime routes. Any static page using a `createContext(null)` + throwing consumer will fail at build time without edge runtime config.
109: 
110: The `getServerSideProps` export on `/` (and `/fixed`, `/simulate-bug`) makes those pages dynamic, opting them out of static prerendering. That's why `npm run build` (the fixed state) succeeds.
111: 
112: ---
113: 
114: ## Root Cause in Detail
115: 
116: ### 1. The Edge renderer is used for Pages Router in Next.js 15
117: 
118: Build output and stack traces prove it:
119: 
120: ```
121: react-dom-server.edge.production.js:4189
122: TypeError: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'useContext')
123: ```
124: 
125: This file is the streaming renderer used for Edge Functions. Next.js 15 routes Pages Router through it even on Node.js targets in certain configurations (confirmed in [vercel/next.js#74858](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/discussions/74858) and [vercel/next.js#82366](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/82366)).
126: 
127: ### 2. `renderToReadableStream` does not guarantee render order
128: 
129: `renderToString` renders the full component tree synchronously top-down — `_app` always before any page. `renderToReadableStream` (Web Streams, used by the Edge renderer) can schedule components differently, especially when Suspense or async boundaries are involved. The `{ ps: 'Page' }` before `{ ps: 'App' }` log is direct evidence.
130: 
131: ### 3. `createContext(null)` with a throwing consumer is the trigger
132: 
133: The bug exists in the renderer. But it only manifests as an error when the context consumer throws (or crashes) on null. Libraries that provide a real default are immune:
134: 
135: | Pattern | Vulnerable? |
136: |---|---|
137: | `createContext(null)` + hard throw on null | **Yes** — `useFlagsmith()`, `useStrictContext()` |
138: | `createContext(null)` + non-null assertion `ctx!` | **Yes** — generic `TypeError` |
139: | `createContext(null)` + optional chain `ctx?.value` | **Silently broken** — returns `undefined` |
140: | `createContext(defaultValue)` with a real default | **No** — `next-themes`, `zustand`, `react-query` |
141: 
142: ---
143: 
144: ## Context Architecture in This Repo
145: 
146: Two providers, two different risk profiles, coexisting without conflict:
147: 
148: ```
149: App (_app)
150:   SafeContextProvider        ← createContext(defaultValue) — safe everywhere, no HOC
151:     StrictContextProvider    ← seeded from pageProps.serverContextState
152:       Navbar                 ← reads both; always safe (rendered by _app, never before it)
153:       WrappedPage (HOC export of /fixed)
154:         StrictContextProvider (HOC) ← same serverContextState, inner wins for page
155:           FixedPage
156:             useSafeContext()    → _app's SafeContextProvider ✓
157:             useStrictContext()  → HOC's StrictContextProvider ✓
158: ```
159: 
160: **Why two `StrictContextProvider` instances is not a conflict:** both are seeded from the same `serverContextState` returned by `getServerSideProps`. Neither updates client-side. Values are identical — Navbar and FixedPage see the same flag state.
161: 
162: **Why `Navbar` is safe with only `_app`'s provider:** `Navbar` is inside `_app`'s JSX. React always executes parent before child, so `Navbar` always has the provider above it. The render-order bug only affects `Component` (the page), which Next.js can schedule independently.
163: 
164: ---
165: 
166: ## The Fix — Per-Page Provider HOC
167: 
168: ### `lib/withStrictContext.tsx`
169: 
170: ```ts
171: // Server helper — call in getServerSideProps
172: export async function getServerContextState(userId?: string): Promise<StrictContextValue>
173: 
174: // HOC — wraps page in its own provider seeded from serverContextState
175: export function withStrictContext<P>(PageComponent: React.ComponentType<P>)
176: ```
177: 
178: ### Usage (2 lines per page)
179: 
180: ```tsx
181: // pages/my-page.tsx
182: import { withStrictContext, getServerContextState } from '@/lib/withStrictContext'
183: 
184: function MyPage() {
185:   const ctx = useStrictContext() // always works
186:   return <div>...</div>
187: }
188: 
189: export const getServerSideProps: GetServerSideProps = async () => ({
190:   props: { serverContextState: await getServerContextState() },
191: })
192: 
193: export default withStrictContext(MyPage)
194: ```
195: 
196: ### Why this is render-order safe
197: 
198: `getServerSideProps` runs **before any React rendering**. By the time the component tree is touched, `serverContextState` is already in `pageProps`. The HOC's provider is part of the page's own subtree — it is always above the page component regardless of how `_app` is scheduled.
199: 
200: ### Flagsmith equivalent (`lib/withPageFlags.tsx` in your real app)
201: 
202: ```ts
203: export async function getPageFlags(userId?: string) {
204:   const flagsmith = createFlagsmithInstance()
205:   await flagsmith.init({
206:     environmentID: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FLAGSMITH_KEY!,
207:     ...(userId ? { identity: userId } : {}),
208:   })
209:   return flagsmith.getState()
210: }
211: 
212: export function withPageFlags<P>(PageComponent: React.ComponentType<P>) {
213:   return function WrappedPage({ flagsmithState, ...props }: P & { flagsmithState: IState }) {
214:     const ref = useRef(createFlagsmithInstance())
215:     return (
216:       <FlagsmithProvider flagsmith={ref.current} serverState={flagsmithState}>
217:         <PageComponent {...(props as P)} />
218:       </FlagsmithProvider>
219:     )
220:   }
221: }
222: ```
223: 
